## 1. Maximum and Minumum values

I'll start with one you *probably* have encountered... Or least covered in an introductory class. Computers can only count so high and so low. Java is no exception. Thankfully, Java keeps these values in conviently-named variables called `MAX_VALUE` and `MIN_VALUE`. Each of [the numerical wrapper classes for the Java primitives](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/java/data/numberclasses.html) have one of each of these variables.

So what happens if you try to go higher or lower than these numbers, by, say, adding or subtracting? You'll get overflow and underflow, respectively. That is, the high value will flow from the max to the min, while the low value will flow from the min to the max. Take this code for example:

{% highlight java %}
int maxInt = Integer.MAX_VALUE;
int minInt = Integer.MIN_VALUE;

System.out.println("max:\t" + maxInt);
System.out.println("min:\t" + minInt);

maxInt++;
minInt--;

System.out.println("\nmax:\t" + maxInt);
System.out.println("min:\t" + minInt);
{% endhighlight %}

The output is as follows:

```
max:	2147483647
min:	-2147483648

```

## 2. String Length

How long can a `String` be? The `String` class keeps the characters in an array, and arrays are indexed by `ints`. That means a `String` can potentially have `Integer.MAX_VALUE` characters. But you'll probably run out of memory long before that.

See the following code:

{% highlight java %}
String longString = "aaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaaa";
int stringLength = longString.length();

try {
    while(true) {
        stringLength = longString.length();
        longString += longString;
    }
} catch(Throwable e) {
    System.out.println("Failed at string length " + stringLength);
    System.out.println(e.getClass().getName());
}
{% endhighlight %}

Here is the output:

```
Failed at string length 411041792
java.lang.OutOfMemoryError
```

If you ever need to process a very large amount of text, you'll need a data structure other than just a `String`.
